offsets.text: Scottnema is well adapted to dry, saline soil and known to be frequent and abundant at high elevations44,53. Our Scottnema GLMM confirms this. Eudor- ylaimus, too, is known to be well adapted to the Antarctic environment. However, studies of its ecology have highlighted that this species prefers moister conditions and relatively lower salinity than Scottnema, which might also be due to the fact that the Antarctic species of this genus can feed on algae35,44. Our Eudorylaimus GLMM is consistent with this notion.

Scottnema is adapted to high salinity and low moisture and tolerate conditions under which Plectus would not survive (with or without competition). Plectus dominates only when soil moisture is much higher and salinity is lower than the average levels of MDVs.
Scottnema is stress tolerant and can survive in most MDV soil, being also able to grow optimally at low temperatures (optimum at ~10 C°)45, whereas Plectus ﬂour- ishes at higher temperatures56.
